The '''cordax''' ({{lang-grc|Κόρδαξ}}),<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dko%2Frdac Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, A Greek-English Lexicon "κόρδαξ"]</ref> was a provocative, licentious, and often obscene mask dance<ref name="eb">{{Cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-22101/Western-dance|title=Dance in Classical Greece|accessdate=2008-03-07|work=Encyclopædia Britannica}}</ref> of [[ancient Greek comedy]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jXSoy8lmfrEC&lpg=PA25&ots=yvraD0vjmy&dq=kordax%20dance&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q=kordax%20dance&f=false|title=Dance and Greek Drama by Bernard Gredley|work=Drama, Dance, and Music By James Redmond (M.A.)}}</ref><ref name="cd">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cs.utk.edu/~mclennan/BA/JO-CD.html |title=Dionysian Meditations |accessdate=2008-03-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217225017/http://www.cs.utk.edu/~mclennan/BA/JO-CD.html |archivedate=2008-02-17 |df= }}</ref> In his play ''[[The Clouds]],'' [[Aristophanes]] complains that other playwrights of his time try to hide the feebleness of their plays by bringing an old woman onto the stage to dance the cordax. He notes with pride that his patrons will not find such gimmicks in his plays. The dance can be compared with the modern ''[[Tsifteteli]]''.<ref>[https://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&tbo=1&hl=el&q=cordax+tsifteteli&btnG=#hl=el&tbo=1&tbm=bks&sa=X&ei=YFViTpfjA9KM4gSb0LCjCg&ved=0CCgQBSgA&q=%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%81%CE%B4%CE%B1%CE%BE+%CF%84%CF%83%CE%B9%CF%86%CF%84%CE%B5%CF%84%CE%B5%CE%BB%CE%B9&spell=1&bav=on.2,or.r_gc.r_pw.&fp=95cd58ce19f03be8&biw=1680&bih=860 Tsifteteli - kordax], ''Hē Lexē'': volumes 21-28</ref>
[[Petronius Arbiter]] in his [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[novel]] the ''[[Satyricon]]'' has Trimalchio boast to his dinner guests that no one dances the cordax better than his wife, Fortunata. The nature of this dance is described in the [[satires of Juvenal]], who says "the girls encouraged by applause sink to the ground with tremulous buttocks." The poet [[Horace]] and playwright [[Plautus]] refer to the same dance as ''iconici motus''.
Juvenal makes specific mention of the ''testarum crepitus'' (clicking of castanets). In the earlier Greek form, finger cymbals were used.
