{{notability|date=April 2017}}
'''Engaged Citizenship''' is the active participation of a [[citizen]] under the law of a sovereign nation discussing and educating themselves in [[politics]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Justin|last2=Wahl‐Jorgensen|first2=Karin|last3=Inthorn|first3=Sanna|date=2004-05-01|title=Images of citizenship on television news: constructing a passive public|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/1461670042000211140|journal=Journalism Studies|volume=5|issue=2|pages=153–164|doi=10.1080/1461670042000211140|issn=1461-670X}}</ref>Engaged citizens are considered independent, and assertive, and concern themselves with others' problems. ie: Organizers of protests look for engaged citizens to be involved and rally behind their cause; often stalling or creating political changes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.ucsusa.org/ken-kimmell/is-progress-stalled-on-clean-energy|title=Is Progress Stalled on Clean Energy? Nah. Look at What States are Doing.|date=2017-04-20|work=Union of Concerned Scientists|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref>

== Changes & Media Coverage ==

Developments in [[social media]] and [[media literacy]] have changed how scholars begin to look at, and define engaged citizenship.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mihailidis|first=Paul|last2=Thevenin|first2=Benjamin|date=2013-11-01|title=Media Literacy as a Core Competency for Engaged Citizenship in Participatory Democracy|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0002764213489015|journal=American Behavioral Scientist|language=en|volume=57|issue=11|pages=1611–1622|doi=10.1177/0002764213489015|issn=0002-7642}}</ref> Engaged citizenship in politics can lead to an apparent consumption of the engaged person rather than offering people with an informed, active opinion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/opinion/article_feec5004-1300-11e7-b539-a7072c470f37.html|title=Guest column: When engaged citizens become consumed, politics disrupt lives, affect personal happiness|last=FAUCHEUX|first=RON|work=The Advocate|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref> Social media sites let people spread information, and create events to provide opportunities for engaged citizenship.<ref name=thewire>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/118679/social-media-world-politics/|title=Can Social Media, Loud and Inclusive, Fix World Politics?|last=Fakhoury|first=Rania|website=thewire.in|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>

Social media and the internet provide a public access point to government affairs, and policies, away from townhall meetings, creating communities with similar concerns to recognize the pitfalls of governments and government policies.<ref name=thewire />

