'''Fool's literature''' was a literary tradition in [[medieval Europe]] in which [[fool (stock character)|the stock character of a fool]] was used as an allegory to satirize the contemporary society.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/212767/fools-literature "Fool's literature"], ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]''</ref>
==Notable examples== * ''[[:de:Der Ring (Lehrgedicht)|Der Ring]]'' (1410, ''The Ring''), a satirical poem by [[Heinrich Wittenwiler]] * ''Daß Narrenschyff ad Narragoniam'' (1494; ''[[Ship of Fools (satire)|Ship of Fools]]''), a poem by the German satirist [[Sebastian Brant]] *''Moriae Encomium, sive Stultitiae Laus'' (1509, ''[[The Praise of Folly]]''), by [[Erasmus of Rotterdam]] *''Narrenbeschwörung'' (1512; ''Exorcism of Fools''), ''Die Schelmenzunft'' (1512); ''Die Gäuchmatt'' (1519, ''Fools' Meadow''), ''Die Mühle von Schwindelsheim und Gretmüllerin Jahrzeit'' by [[Thomas Murner]]
